<BLOCK1><TI TOCID="I">AFFIDAVIT</TI>
<P>I Daniel Rozon CA, CIRP, Trustee in bankruptcy hereby make oath and say:
<P1>1. I am a Senior Vice-President, a Chartered Accountant and Trustee in Bankruptcy with Grant Thornton Limited (&ldquo;GT&rdquo;) and the information on which this Affidavit is based is from the documents obtained from and discussions with Joseph Edward Hendsbee;</P1>
<P1>2. Green Hunt Wedlake Inc. (predecessor firm of GT) was the Trustee in the bankruptcy of Joseph Edward Hendsbee (&ldquo;Hendsbee&rdquo;) filed on May 11, 2004 and GT is the Administrator of the Consumer Proposal of Hendsbee filed on March 28, 2013;</P1>
<P1>3. Hendsbee was a self-employed flooring installer/carpenter for approximately 14 years until September 2012 at which time he became an employee of D. Procure Construction (&ldquo;Procure&rdquo;).</P1>
<P1>4. Hendsbee is a single father supporting two young children aged 5 and 4 years old. His estranged wife has no contact with him or the children. He receives no support from his estranged wife.</P1>
<P1>5. He earns $15.00 per hour as shown on the payslip attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;A&rdquo;</BOLD>. Income tax and other deductions are now being taken directly from his pay cheque as noted in the same exhibit;</P1>
<P1>6. In &ldquo;good weeks&rdquo; his puts in 40 hours of work for Procure but on average it is much lower, especially during the winter months;</P1>
<P1>7. Attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;B&rdquo;</BOLD> is the Income and Expense Statement Hendsbee submitted with his Consumer Proposal. The available monthly income of the family unit is $1,000 after child care expenses.</P1>
<P1>8. The guideline according to the Surplus Income Standards issued by the Office of the Superintendent of Bankruptcy (OSB) for a family of three persons is $3,070. Hendsbee's family unit income is substantially below the guideline.</P1></P>
<BLOCK2><TI>Bankruptcy</TI>
<P><P1>9. Hendsbee's sole creditor in the bankruptcy filed on May 11, 2004 was Canada Revenue Agency (&ldquo;CRA&rdquo;) in the amount of $64,764.</P1>
<P1>10. Hendsbee was granted a Conditional Order of Discharge on October 1, 2005 requiring him to pay $7,200 and file his 2004, 2005 and 2006 income tax and H ST returns and pay the amounts due for those years. A copy of the Conditional Order of Discharge is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;C&rdquo;;</BOLD></P1>
<P1>11. Hendsbee paid the amount of $7,200 to the bankrupt estate as required in the Conditional Order of Discharge but did not deliver proof that his 2004, 2005 and 2006 income tax and HST returns had been filled or paid;</P1>
<P1>12. Green Hunt Wedlake Inc./Grant Thornton Limited was discharged as Trustee to the bankruptcy on December 29, 2008.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Years subsequent to the May 2004 Bankruptcy</TI>
<P><P1>13. By his own admission Hendsbee has told GT that he was not diligent in filing his income tax and HST returns when he was self-employed;</P1>
<P1>14. Hendsbee has advised GT of the following:
<P2>a. CRA issued arbitrary income tax and HST assessments for the years 2004 to 2008 and possibly for some of the subsequent years;</P2>
<P2>b. Hendsbee believes that he filed tax returns for certain years after 2004, including 2010, 2011 and 2012;</P2>
<P2>c. From 2004 to 2012, his main source of revenue was from work as a sub-contractor for Vintage Hardwood Floors (&ldquo;Vintage&rdquo;);</P2>
<P2>d. The gross amount he was receiving from Vintage was approximately $50,000 per year (which was at least 95% of his gross income before business expenses);</P2>
<P2>e. For a period of at least 3 years there was an outstanding Requirement To Pay served on Vintage by CRA;</P2>
<P2>f. CRA was paid 40% of the gross amount payable to Hendsbee for at least 3 years which represents a total of approximately $60,000 (40% &times; $50,000 &times; 3 years) by Vintage during that time period. The total actual amount could be substantially more;</P2>
<P2>g. His business related expenses were approximately $15,000 per year; therefore his net yearly taxable income was approximately $35,000 ($50,000 less 15,000). Using an effective tax rate of 20% Hensdbee would have owed approximately $7,000 a year in taxes.</P2>
<P2>h. He has further advised that he has few or no remaining records for the years 2004 to 2008;</P2></P1>
<P1>15. As an experienced Chartered Accountant, I am of the opinion that it would cost at least several thousand dollars to reconstitute Hendsbee's accounting records and prepare 6&ndash;9 years of income tax and HST returns and reconcile those with the arbitrary assessments issued by CRA. Based on his current income, Hendsbee cannot afford to pay an accountant to perform that work.</P1>
<P1>16. Based on the above, I am of the opinion that it is reasonable to conclude the following:
<P2>a. Any taxes Hendsbee would have owed for 2004, 2005 and 2006 have been paid by virtue of the payments made by Vintage to CRA under the Requirement to Pay;</P2>
<P2>b. Based on more than 30 years in practice as a Chartered Accountant and a Trustee in bankruptcy, it is my experience that when CRA issues arbitrary assessments, those assessments tend to be significantly higher compared to the returns which should normally have been filed by a taxpayer, for the following reasons: gross income is usually over estimated; no provision is made for tax deductible business expenses; minimal or no provision are made for tax credits; and no credits are taken when estimating HST.</P2>
<P2>c. The arbitrary assessments issued by CRA for the years 2004, 2005 and 2006 are tantamount to Hendsbee having filed the returns for those years;</P2>
<P2>d. If Hendsbee could afford to pay an accountant to reconstitute his records from 2004 to 2008 and submit accurate returns, it is plausible and highly probable that Hendsbee has overpaid his taxes to CRA for that period of time and would actually be due a significant refund;</P2></P1>
<P1>17. Based on paragraph 16 above, it is reasonable to conclude that Hendsbee has fulfilled the remaining conditions of his Conditional Order of Discharge and should have been granted an Absolute Order of Discharge.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Consumer Proposal</TI>
<P><P1>18. On March 8, 2013, CRA issued a new Requirement to Pay to Daniel Procure, Hendsbee's employer, for an amount of $20,024. A copy is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;D&rdquo;</BOLD>. That amount has now increased to $99,247 as per <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;F&rdquo;</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>19. Hendsbee's only creditor in his Consumer Proposal was CRA;</P1>
<P1>20. GT has not investigated the source of the tax owing but it is probably a balance of amounts due under the arbitrary assessments of 2004 to 2008 and subsequent returns Hendsbee filed prior to becoming an employee of Procure in 2012.</P1>
<P1>21. As indicated in paragraph 28 above, Hendsbee probably did not owe money to CRA when he filed his Consumer Proposal but he cannot afford to have proper income tax and HST returns prepared;</P1>
<P1>22. Hendsbee filed a Consumer Proposal with GT on March 28, 2013, a copy of which is attached as <BOLD>Exhibit &ldquo;E&rdquo;</BOLD>;</P1>
<P1>23. GT's position was that based on the conclusion reached in paragraph 16 above, Hendsbee had complied with the Conditional Order of Discharge in his bankruptcy and was entitled to file a Consumer Proposal;</P1>
<P1>24. As Administrator, GT issued several Notices of Stay of Proceedings to CRA and to Procure regarding the March 2013 Requirement to Pay;</P1>
<P1>25. There is a difference of opinion between GT, CRA and the OSB as to whether Hendsbee was entitled to file a Consumer Proposal, That debate is now moot because Hendsbee is in default of his Consumer Proposal and he does not have sufficient income to make payments due to his family obligations.</P1></P></BLOCK2>
<BLOCK2><TI>Conclusion</TI>
<P><P1>26. Hendsbee is the sole provider of 2 young children and is not receiving support from his estranged wife. He has very limited income and the family unit income is substantially below the OSB surplus income guidelines for a family of 3 persons and would not have the means to comply with the outstanding issues of the Conditional Order of Discharge;</P1>
<P1>27. Hendsbee needs the relief offered by a second bankruptcy under the Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act;</P1>
<P1>28. As stated in paragraph 16 above, GT's position is that Hendsbee has complied with the outstanding terms of the Conditional Order of Discharge.</P1></P>
<P>I make this this affidavit in support of the Application for Directions by GT of April 1, 2014 and for no improper purpose.</P>
<P><BOLD>DATED</BOLD> at Halifax, Nova Scotia, this 1<SUP>st</SUP> day of April, 2014.</P>
